# CSV Parser - Usage Examples

Comprehensive examples demonstrating all features of the CSV parser library.

## Installation

### TypeScript
```typescript
import { parseCSV, CSVResult, CSVOptions } from './csv-parser';
```

### JavaScript
```javascript
const { parseCSV } = require('./csv-parser.js');
```

## Basic Parsing

### Example 1: Simple CSV
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,NYC
Jane,25,LA`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows);
// Output:
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, city: 'NYC' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, city: 'LA' }
// ]
```

### Example 2: Check for Errors
```javascript
const csv = `name,age
John,30
Jane,25,EXTRA_COLUMN`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
if (result.errors.length > 0) {
  console.log('Parse errors found:');
  result.errors.forEach(err => {
    console.log(`  Row ${err.row}: ${err.message}`);
  });
}
// Output:
// Parse errors found:
//   Row 3: Expected 2 columns, got 3
```

## Quoted Fields

### Example 3: Preserving Commas in Fields
```javascript
const csv = `name,address,phone
John,"123 Main St, Apt 5","555-1234"
Jane,"456 Oak Ave, Suite 100","555-5678"`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].address);
// Output: "123 Main St, Apt 5"
```

### Example 4: Handling Special Characters
```javascript
const csv = `product,description,price
Apple,"Delicious, red, sweet",1.99
Banana,"Yellow, organic, fresh",0.89`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
result.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log(`${row.product}: ${row.description} - $${row.price}`);
});
// Output:
// Apple: Delicious, red, sweet - $1.99
// Banana: Yellow, organic, fresh - $0.89
```

## Escaped Quotes

### Example 5: Quotes Within Quoted Fields
```javascript
const csv = `name,review
John,"He said ""Great product!"""
Jane,"She replied ""Yes, amazing!"""`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].review);
// Output: He said "Great product!"
```

### Example 6: Complex Quoted Content
```javascript
const csv = `title,content
Story,"She said ""I can't believe it"" and left."
Letter,"Quote: ""Don't worry, be happy."""`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].content);
// Output: She said "I can't believe it" and left.
```

## Custom Delimiters

### Example 7: Tab-Separated Values (TSV)
```javascript
const tsv = `name\tage\tcity
John\t30\tNYC
Jane\t25\tLA`;

const result = parseCSV(tsv, { delimiter: '\t' });
console.log(result.rows);
// Output:
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, city: 'NYC' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, city: 'LA' }
// ]
```

### Example 8: Semicolon-Separated
```javascript
const csv = `name;email;phone
John;john@example.com;555-1234
Jane;jane@example.com;555-5678`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: ';' });
console.log(result.rows[0].email);
// Output: john@example.com
```

### Example 9: Pipe-Separated with Custom Quotes
```javascript
const csv = `name|address|notes
John|'123 Main St, Apt 5'|'Good location'
Jane|'456 Oak Ave, Suite 100'|'Quiet area'`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, {
  delimiter: '|',
  quoteChar: "'"
});
console.log(result.rows[0].address);
// Output: 123 Main St, Apt 5
```

### Example 10: Windows Line Endings
```javascript
const csv = `name,age\r\nJohn,30\r\nJane,25`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, {
  lineSeparator: '\r\n'
});
console.log(result.rows.length);
// Output: 2
```

## Type Coercion

### Example 11: Automatic Number Detection
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,height,weight
John,30,5.9,180
Jane,25,5.4,120`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].age);      // "number"
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].height);   // "number"
console.log(result.rows[0].age);             // 30 (integer)
console.log(result.rows[0].height);          // 5.9 (float)
```

### Example 12: Boolean Detection
```javascript
const csv = `name,active,verified
John,true,false
Jane,false,true
Bob,TRUE,FALSE`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].active);   // true (boolean)
console.log(result.rows[0].verified);  // false (boolean)
console.log(typeof result.rows[1].active);  // "boolean"
```

### Example 13: Null Handling
```javascript
const csv = `name,email,phone
John,john@example.com,
Jane,,555-1234
Bob,null,NULL`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].phone);    // null
console.log(result.rows[1].email);    // null
console.log(result.rows[2].email);    // null
console.log(result.rows[2].phone);    // null
```

### Example 14: String Preservation
```javascript
const csv = `name,status,code
John,active,A123
Jane,inactive,B456`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].status);  // "string"
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].code);    // "string"
console.log(result.rows[0].code);           // "A123" (string, not number)
```

### Example 15: Mixed Types
```javascript
const csv = `id,name,score,active,notes
1,John,95.5,true,Great student
2,Jane,88.0,false,Needs improvement
3,Bob,null,true,`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
// Row 1: { id: 1, name: 'John', score: 95.5, active: true, notes: 'Great student' }
// Row 2: { id: 2, name: 'Jane', score: 88.0, active: false, notes: 'Needs improvement' }
// Row 3: { id: 3, name: 'Bob', score: null, active: true, notes: null }
```

## Filtering

### Example 16: Filter by Number
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,NYC
Jane,25,LA
Bob,35,NYC
Alice,28,Chicago`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const adults = result.filter(row => row.age >= 30);
console.log(adults.count());           // 2
console.log(adults.rows[0].name);      // "John"
console.log(adults.rows[1].name);      // "Bob"
```

### Example 17: Filter by String
```javascript
const result = parseCSV(csv);
const nycResidents = result.filter(row => row.city === 'NYC');
console.log(nycResidents.count());      // 2
```

### Example 18: Complex Filter
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,salary,department
John,30,80000,Engineering
Jane,25,65000,Marketing
Bob,35,90000,Engineering
