# CSV Parser - Usage Examples

Comprehensive examples demonstrating all features of the CSV parser library.

## Installation

### TypeScript
```typescript
import { parseCSV, CSVResult, CSVOptions } from './csv-parser';
```

### JavaScript
```javascript
const { parseCSV } = require('./csv-parser.js');
```

## Basic Parsing

### Example 1: Simple CSV
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,NYC
Jane,25,LA`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows);
// Output:
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, city: 'NYC' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, city: 'LA' }
// ]
```

### Example 2: Check for Errors
```javascript
const csv = `name,age
John,30
Jane,25,EXTRA_COLUMN`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
if (result.errors.length > 0) {
  console.log('Parse errors found:');
  result.errors.forEach(err => {
    console.log(`  Row ${err.row}: ${err.message}`);
  });
}
// Output:
// Parse errors found:
//   Row 3: Expected 2 columns, got 3
```

## Quoted Fields

### Example 3: Preserving Commas in Fields
```javascript
const csv = `name,address,phone
John,"123 Main St, Apt 5","555-1234"
Jane,"456 Oak Ave, Suite 100","555-5678"`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].address);
// Output: "123 Main St, Apt 5"
```

### Example 4: Handling Special Characters
```javascript
const csv = `product,description,price
Apple,"Delicious, red, sweet",1.99
Banana,"Yellow, organic, fresh",0.89`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
result.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log(`${row.product}: ${row.description} - $${row.price}`);
});
// Output:
// Apple: Delicious, red, sweet - $1.99
// Banana: Yellow, organic, fresh - $0.89
```

## Escaped Quotes

### Example 5: Quotes Within Quoted Fields
```javascript
const csv = `name,review
John,"He said ""Great product!"""
Jane,"She replied ""Yes, amazing!"""`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].review);
// Output: He said "Great product!"
```

### Example 6: Complex Quoted Content
```javascript
const csv = `title,content
Story,"She said ""I can't believe it"" and left."
Letter,"Quote: ""Don't worry, be happy."""`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].content);
// Output: She said "I can't believe it" and left.
```

## Custom Delimiters

### Example 7: Tab-Separated Values (TSV)
```javascript
const tsv = `name\tage\tcity
John\t30\tNYC
Jane\t25\tLA`;

const result = parseCSV(tsv, { delimiter: '\t' });
console.log(result.rows);
// Output:
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, city: 'NYC' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, city: 'LA' }
// ]
```

### Example 8: Semicolon-Separated
```javascript
const csv = `name;email;phone
John;john@example.com;555-1234
Jane;jane@example.com;555-5678`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: ';' });
console.log(result.rows[0].email);
// Output: john@example.com
```

### Example 9: Pipe-Separated with Custom Quotes
```javascript
const csv = `name|address|notes
John|'123 Main St, Apt 5'|'Good location'
Jane|'456 Oak Ave, Suite 100'|'Quiet area'`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, {
  delimiter: '|',
  quoteChar: "'"
});
console.log(result.rows[0].address);
// Output: 123 Main St, Apt 5
```

### Example 10: Windows Line Endings
```javascript
const csv = `name,age\r\nJohn,30\r\nJane,25`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, {
  lineSeparator: '\r\n'
});
console.log(result.rows.length);
// Output: 2
```

## Type Coercion

### Example 11: Automatic Number Detection
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,height,weight
John,30,5.9,180
Jane,25,5.4,120`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].age);      // "number"
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].height);   // "number"
console.log(result.rows[0].age);             // 30 (integer)
console.log(result.rows[0].height);          // 5.9 (float)
```

### Example 12: Boolean Detection
```javascript
const csv = `name,active,verified
John,true,false
Jane,false,true
Bob,TRUE,FALSE`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].active);   // true (boolean)
console.log(result.rows[0].verified);  // false (boolean)
console.log(typeof result.rows[1].active);  // "boolean"
```

### Example 13: Null Handling
```javascript
const csv = `name,email,phone
John,john@example.com,
Jane,,555-1234
Bob,null,NULL`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].phone);    // null
console.log(result.rows[1].email);    // null
console.log(result.rows[2].email);    // null
console.log(result.rows[2].phone);    // null
```

### Example 14: String Preservation
```javascript
const csv = `name,status,code
John,active,A123
Jane,inactive,B456`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].status);  // "string"
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].code);    // "string"
console.log(result.rows[0].code);           // "A123" (string, not number)
```

### Example 15: Mixed Types
```javascript
const csv = `id,name,score,active,notes
1,John,95.5,true,Great student
2,Jane,88.0,false,Needs improvement
3,Bob,null,true,`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
// Row 1: { id: 1, name: 'John', score: 95.5, active: true, notes: 'Great student' }
// Row 2: { id: 2, name: 'Jane', score: 88.0, active: false, notes: 'Needs improvement' }
// Row 3: { id: 3, name: 'Bob', score: null, active: true, notes: null }
```

## Filtering

### Example 16: Filter by Number
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,NYC
Jane,25,LA
Bob,35,NYC
Alice,28,Chicago`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const adults = result.filter(row => row.age >= 30);
console.log(adults.count());           // 2
console.log(adults.rows[0].name);      // "John"
console.log(adults.rows[1].name);      // "Bob"
```

### Example 17: Filter by String
```javascript
const result = parseCSV(csv);
const nycResidents = result.filter(row => row.city === 'NYC');
console.log(nycResidents.count());      // 2
```

### Example 18: Complex Filter
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,salary,department
John,30,80000,Engineering
Jane,25,65000,Marketing
Bob,35,90000,Engineering
Alice,28,75000,Marketing`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const highEarningEngineers = result.filter(
  row => row.department === 'Engineering' && row.salary > 85000
);
console.log(highEarningEngineers.count());  // 1
console.log(highEarningEngineers.rows[0].name);  // "Bob"
```

## Aggregation

### Example 19: Sum Values
```javascript
const csv = `product,price,quantity
Apple,1.99,10
Banana,0.89,20
Orange,2.49,15`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const totalPrice = result.sum('price');
const totalQty = result.sum('quantity');
console.log(`Total price: $${totalPrice.toFixed(2)}`);  // Total price: $5.37
console.log(`Total quantity: ${totalQty}`);              // Total quantity: 45
```

### Example 20: Average Values
```javascript
const csv = `month,revenue
January,50000
February,55000
March,60000
April,45000`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const avgRevenue = result.average('revenue');
console.log(`Average revenue: $${avgRevenue.toLocaleString()}`);
// Output: Average revenue: $52,500
```

### Example 21: Count Rows
```javascript
const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(`Total rows: ${result.count()}`);
```

### Example 22: Group By Column
```javascript
const csv = `name,city,age
John,NYC,30
Jane,LA,25
Bob,NYC,35
Alice,Chicago,28
Carol,LA,32`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const grouped = result.groupBy('city');

console.log('NYC residents:');
grouped.get('NYC').forEach(row => {
  console.log(`  ${row.name} (${row.age})`);
});
// Output:
// NYC residents:
//   John (30)
//   Bob (35)

console.log(`LA residents count: ${grouped.get('LA').length}`);  // 2
```

## Chaining Operations

### Example 23: Filter and Then Aggregate
```javascript
const csv = `name,city,salary
John,NYC,80000
Jane,LA,75000
Bob,NYC,90000
Alice,Chicago,70000`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const nycAverageSalary = result
  .filter(row => row.city === 'NYC')
  .average('salary');

console.log(`NYC average salary: $${nycAverageSalary.toLocaleString()}`);
// Output: NYC average salary: $85,000
```

### Example 24: Group and Analyze
```javascript
const csv = `name,department,salary
John,Engineering,80000
Jane,Marketing,65000
Bob,Engineering,90000
Alice,Marketing,75000
Carol,Sales,70000`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
const grouped = result.groupBy('department');

// Analyze each department
for (const [dept, rows] of grouped) {
  const avgSalary = rows.reduce((sum, r) => sum + r.salary, 0) / rows.length;
  console.log(`${dept}: ${rows.length} people, avg salary: $${avgSalary}`);
}
// Output:
// Engineering: 2 people, avg salary: $85000
// Marketing: 2 people, avg salary: $70000
// Sales: 1 people, avg salary: $70000
```

## Error Handling

### Example 25: Graceful Error Handling
```javascript
const csv = `name,age,email
John,30,john@example.com
Jane,25
Bob,35,bob@example.com
Alice,28,alice@example.com,EXTRA`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(`Successfully parsed: ${result.count()} rows`);
console.log(`Parse errors: ${result.errors.length}`);

result.errors.forEach(err => {
  console.log(`Row ${err.row}: ${err.message}`);
});
// Output:
// Successfully parsed: 2 rows
// Parse errors: 2
// Row 3: Expected 3 columns, got 2
// Row 5: Expected 3 columns, got 4
```

## Real-World Scenarios

### Example 26: Sales Data Analysis
```javascript
const salesCSV = `date,salesperson,region,amount,product
2024-01-15,John,East,1500,"Widget A"
2024-01-16,Jane,West,2000,"Widget B"
2024-01-17,Bob,East,1200,"Widget A"
2024-01-18,Alice,Central,3000,"Widget C"
2024-01-19,John,East,1800,"Widget B"`;

const result = parseCSV(salesCSV);

// Total sales by region
const byRegion = result.groupBy('region');
console.log('Sales by region:');
for (const [region, sales] of byRegion) {
  const total = sales.reduce((sum, s) => sum + s.amount, 0);
  console.log(`  ${region}: $${total.toLocaleString()}`);
}

// Top performer
const topSales = result.rows.reduce((max, row) => 
  row.amount > max.amount ? row : max
);
console.log(`Top sale: ${topSales.salesperson} - $${topSales.amount}`);
```

### Example 27: Product Inventory
```javascript
const inventoryCSV = `sku,name,quantity,price,in_stock
SKU001,Laptop,5,999.99,true
SKU002,Mouse,50,29.99,true
SKU003,Keyboard,0,79.99,false
SKU004,Monitor,10,299.99,true`;

const result = parseCSV(inventoryCSV);

// Items in stock
const inStock = result.filter(row => row.in_stock === true);
console.log(`Items in stock: ${inStock.count()}`);

// Total inventory value
const totalValue = result.rows.reduce(
  (sum, row) => sum + (row.quantity * row.price), 0
);
console.log(`Total inventory value: $${totalValue.toFixed(2)}`);

// Out of stock items
const outOfStock = result.filter(row => row.in_stock === false);
console.log('Out of stock:');
outOfStock.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log(`  ${row.name}`);
});
```

### Example 28: Student Grades
```javascript
const gradesCSV = `name,math,science,english,average
John,85,90,88,87.67
Jane,92,95,90,92.33
Bob,78,82,80,80.00
Alice,88,85,92,88.33`;

const result = parseCSV(gradesCSV);

// Find high achievers (average >= 90)
const highAchievers = result.filter(row => row.average >= 90);
console.log(`High achievers: ${highAchievers.count()}`);

// Class average
const classAverage = result.average('average');
console.log(`Class average: ${classAverage.toFixed(2)}`);

// Best student in each subject
['math', 'science', 'english'].forEach(subject => {
  const best = result.rows.reduce((max, row) =>
    row[subject] > max[subject] ? row : max
  );
  console.log(`Best in ${subject}: ${best.name} (${best[subject]})`);
});
```

---

These examples cover all major features of the CSV parser. For more details, see the README.md and IMPLEMENTATION_GUIDE.md files.

